[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Created by super agent Create a comprehensive, professional slide presentation based on \"The Definitive Guide to Writing Unaware Ads (Full Masterclass)\" by Luke Iha. The presentation should cover all the key concepts from the video with clear visual hierarchy, engaging formatting, and appropriate number of slides based on the content richness. Include: 1. Title slide 2. What are unaware ads and why they matter 3. Eugene Schwartz's stages of awareness explained 4. Why unaware ads are the hardest and most valuable 5. The hidden advantage of cracking cold traffic 6. Quotes from top marketers on unaware ads 7. Real unaware ad examples (Gundry, Grounding Well, PupLabs) 8. The curiosity + relevance framework 9. The specificity spectrum (body → health → blood sugar → neuropathy) 10. How unaware ads compare to other awareness levels 11. 10 proven unaware ad types (paradoxes, conspiracies, warning signs, stories, etc.) 12. Triggers that always work (NASA, tribes, Amish, Nobel Prize, Harvard) 13. Stealing organic hooks (cook your algorithm method) 14. Worldview principles explained (validate or contradict beliefs) 15. Blair Warren's 5 principles + additions (confirm suspicions, throw rocks at enemies) 16. Vectors of winning angles (pattern recognition + AI) 17. The specificity spectrum details 18. Open loops that stick 19. Unaware ad structure breakdown 20. Grounding Well ad dissection (line-by-line analysis) 21. Summary and key takeaways 22. Action steps and implementation Use professional design with: - Clear visual hierarchy - Engaging graphics and icons - Data visualization where appropriate - Color-coded sections - Bullet points and short phrases (not dense paragraphs) - Strategic use of white space - Professional marketing/advertising theme - Examples and case studies highlighted visually I'll create a comprehensive, professional slide presentation on \"The Definitive Guide to Writing Unaware Ads\" by Luke Iha. Let me start by initializing the project and then building out all the slides with detailed content, visual elements, and tactical information. Using Tool | Presentation New presentation: The Definitive Guide to Writing Unaware Ads I'll create a comprehensive masterclass presentation on \"The Definitive Guide to Writing Unaware Ads\" by Luke Iha. Let me start by building a detailed outline and action plan for 25-30 slides covering all the key concepts. Using Tool | Presentation Insert 28 slides at page 1 with outline planning Outline 28 / 28 pages 1 The Definitive Guide to Writing Unaware Ads - Full masterclass by Luke Iha - How to win cold traffic with curiosity + relevance - Professional marketing playbook: frameworks, examples, and execution 2 How to Use This Masterclass - What you’ll learn: psychology, frameworks, examples, execution - Built for paid social, native, YouTube, email pre-landers - Color key: Strategy (blue), Psychology (orange), Frameworks (teal), Examples (purple), Execution (green) 3 What Are Unaware Ads — And Why They Matter - Audience does not know the problem, solution, or your product - Goal: spark curiosity, then bridge to a relevant problem - Why it matters: scale, cheaper clicks, new markets, durable moats 4 Eugene Schwartz: 5 Stages of Awareness - Unaware → Problem-aware → Solution-aware → Product-aware → Most aware - Unaware: lead with idea/insight; no product push - Progressively reveal mechanism and relevance 5 Why Unaware Ads Are Hardest (and Most Valuable) - You must create context before selling - Highest creative skill: pattern recognition + narrative + mechanism - Biggest prize: own the category conversation; CAC advantage compounds 6 Hidden Advantages of Cracking Cold Traffic - Broader TAM and top-of-funnel growth - Creative learnings lift all channels (email, SEO, affiliates) - Resilience to platform shifts; demand generation vs demand capture 7 What the Greats Say - Eugene Schwartz: \"You cannot create desire; you can only channel it.\" - David Ogilvy: \"When you’ve written your headline, you’ve spent 80 cents of your dollar.\" - Blair Warren: People act for those who confirm suspicions and help throw rocks at enemies 8 Real Unaware Ads: Gundry, Grounding Well, PupLabs - Dr. Gundry: curiosity around everyday foods and hidden mechanisms (e.g., lectins) - Grounding Well: counterintuitive health mechanism (earthing/grounding) framed via authority - PupLabs: odd canine habit → surprising health link → simple fix 9 Curiosity + Relevance Framework - Curiosity: a pattern break that opens a loop - Relevance: anchor to the audience’s identity/symptom/context - Bridge: tease mechanism; promise clarity or control; defer product 10 The Specificity Spectrum (from Broad to Niche) - Body → Health → Blood sugar → Neuropathy - Rule: start broad enough to earn attention, narrow fast to earn belief - Visualize as funnel: curiosity breadth narrows to specific mechanism 11 How Unaware Differs from Other Awareness Levels - Hook style: curiosity vs direct benefit/offer - Content: insight/story vs comparison/offer stack - CTA: learn/diagnose vs buy/claim coupon 12 10 Proven Unaware Ad Types - Paradoxes: the thing you avoid is the thing you need - Conspiracies: common advice is backwards - Warning signs: silent symptom checklist - Stories: unlikely discovery origin tale - Weird mechanisms: odd nutrient, habit, device - Authority reveals: doctor/professor/engineer insights - Ancient/tribal secrets: Amish, Okinawan, Hadza - New study: Nobel/Harvard/Stanford findings - Forbidden/hidden lists: \"5 foods to avoid\" - Simple tests/diagnostics: 10-second home check 13 Triggers That Always Work (Use Ethically) - NASA, Nobel Prize, Harvard: authority + novelty - Tribes/Amish/Blue Zones: ancestral wisdom - Contrarian doctors/engineers: credentialed rebels - Media patterns: \"Scientists baffled\", \"Engineers discover\" 14 Steal Organic Hooks: Cook Your Algorithm - Pick a niche and follow/save only top hook patterns - Platform immersion: TikTok/YouTube/Reddit/Twitter - Swipe and tag: mechanism, enemy, symptom, identity - Weekly review: cluster and adapt to your offer - Test fast with 5–10 hooks per angle 15 Worldview Principles - Ads work when they validate or productively contradict beliefs - Validate: \"You’re not lazy; the mechanism is hidden\" - Contradict: polite, evidence-backed; offer safer, higher-status stance 16 Blair Warren’s 5 Principles (+ Additions) - Encourage dreams; Justify failures; Allay fears; Confirm suspicions; Help throw rocks at enemies - Add: Protect identity/status; Offer simple control; Provide belonging - Use sparingly; avoid cynicism/manipulation 17 Vectors of Winning Angles (Pattern Recognition + AI) - Angle clusters: Mechanism, Enemy, Authority, Symptom, Identity, Social proof - Use AI: cluster headlines, score novelty/relevance, suggest hybrids - Build an Angle Matrix: hooks × mechanisms × avatars 18 Specificity Spectrum — Deep Dive - Start broad: \"Morning habit ruins energy\" - Narrow: \"Blood sugar spikes after coffee\" - Laser: \"Neuropathy flares from post-coffee glucose crash\" - Transition copy: broad hook → named mechanism → specific symptom 19 Open Loops That Stick - Pattern breaks + unresolved curiosity - Formats: \"the one thing\", \"until I tried this\", \"engineers found\", \"but\" pivots - Always close loops on landers/emails to maintain trust 20 Unaware Ad Structure — Anatomy - Hook: curiosity + relevance - Setup: relatable scene or symptom - Tension: common belief vs new mechanism - Mechanism tease: simple, visual, nameable - Authority/context: credential, study, tribe - Social proof: numbers, testimonials (light) - CTA: learn/see how/test yourself 21 Grounding Well — Line-by-Line Dissection - Headline: counterintuitive claim tied to authority - Line 1: relatable symptom (restless sleep, fatigue) - Line 2: tension (modern insulation vs human design) - Line 3: mechanism tease (grounding/charge balance) - Line 4: authority (engineers/space research reference) - Line 5: social proof (user count, reviews) - CTA: \"See how to try it for 10 minutes tonight\" 22 Gundry + PupLabs — Micro Teardowns - Gundry: \"3 ‘healthy’ foods quietly harming your gut\" → introduces lectin mechanism → simple swaps - PupLabs: \"Odd breath clue reveals gut issue in dogs\" → mechanism bridge → treat-as-test CTA - Lessons: paradox + mechanism + simple control 23 Testing & Optimization Strategy - Creative ladder: Hook → Angle → Mechanism → Offer - 3×3 matrix: hooks × creatives × avatars - Metrics: thumbstop %, 3-sec hold, CTR, CPC, CPA, CVR - Kill/scale rules; rotate angles weekly 24 Common Mistakes to Avoid - Curiosity without relevance (clickbait) - Over-claims/compliance issues - No mechanism bridge; jumps straight to product - Too broad or too niche; no clear next step 25 Implementation Checklist - Define avatars, symptoms, enemies, desired identities - Build angle library; swipe 50–100 organic hooks - Draft 10 hooks × 3 mechanisms × 2 avatars - Produce 5 variations per top 5 hooks - Set test plan, metrics, kill/scale rules 26 Key Frameworks — At a Glance - Curiosity + Relevance + Mechanism bridge - Specificity Spectrum: broad → narrow → laser - Angle Vectors: mechanism, enemy, authority, symptom, identity - Ad Structure: hook, setup, tension, tease, authority, proof, CTA 27 Action Steps & Resources - This week: build swipe file; outline 3 angles; script 10 hooks; produce 10–15 assets - Next week: run 3×3 tests; review metrics; iterate top 20% - Resources: angle matrix template; hook scorecard; compliance checklist 28 Section Break — Q&A / Discussion - Questions on frameworks, examples, or tests? - Identify your first angle to ship in 7 days I'll now create the comprehensive masterclass presentation on \"The Definitive Guide to Writing Unaware Ads\" by Luke Iha. Let me start by building the template slides one by one, then fill in the remaining content. Using Tool | Deep Thinking Total: 13 Tasks 13 Tasks Remaining Create cover slide (Page